Democracy without Popular Connection
Something has happened to democracy in the sense that the government is elected by the people, and it has happened everywhere in the world.
Somehow people have lost faith in elections.
Voter turnout is declining in many countries; in the case of the European Parliament elections, voter turnout was so ridiculously low that the legitimacy of the election result is questionable.
Aside from voter turnout, we have become accustomed to accepting parties or candidates who receive 25% of the votes as "winners".
From Holland through Finland to Argentina and Japan, majority governments are formed based on minorities.
Even the apparent exceptions do not prove the opposite.
Only a few American presidents have been elected by more than 10% of the electorate. In fact, half of the eligible voters in the USA did not even register to participate in the election; of those who registered, half did not vote; of those who voted, less than half voted for the election winner.
Even Tony Blair's "dam-breaking" majority in the UK House of Commons is on shaky ground: The Labour Party received only just over 40% of the votes in the last election in 2002, with a voter turnout of 60%.
Thus, only 24% of the total electorate supported Blair's party.
In most countries, elections look significantly different today than they did twenty, or even fifty, years ago.
What has happened?
One answer is that voters distrust political parties.
Electoral democracy functions in most countries through the mediation of organizations that put forward candidates who stand for specific packages of political options, for a "manifesto" or an "election program."
For a number of reasons, this long-established practice no longer works.
Ideological party programs have lost their power; voters no longer accept the packages put together by the parties, they want to pick and choose for themselves.
Moreover, political parties have become machines composed of tightly organized cores of insiders.
The paradox here is that parties have become even more clique-like with the loss of their specific ideological orientation.
It is more important to belong to them than to share their specific beliefs.
Such developments have alienated parties from voters.
Because most people do not want to belong to any particular party, only a minority plays along with the party game.
This increases public suspicion towards political parties, not least because, like in professional sports, it is expensive to participate.
When the costs are borne by taxpayers, this is resented.
However, without financial support from the state, parties would have to obtain money through channels that are often highly dubious, if not even illegal.
Many of the major political scandals of the last few decades began with the financing of parties and their candidates.
Other indicators - such as the clear decline in memberships - confirm that parties have become unpopular.
Nevertheless, parties are indispensable for a electoral democracy.
The result is an obvious separation between the visible political actors and the electorate.
Because parties are active in parliaments, the effects of this separation concern one of the key institutions of democracy.
People no longer believe that parliaments represent them and thus have the necessary legitimacy to make decisions on their behalf.
At this point, a second, quite independent development comes into play.
People today are more impatient than ever before.
As consumers, they are used to immediate satisfaction.
But as voters, they have to wait before they can feel the results of the election they have cast their votes for.
Sometimes they never see the desired results.
Democracy needs time not only for elections, but also for discussions and careful consideration.
The consumer as a voter, however, will not accept this and therefore turns away.
There are alternatives. Yet each has its own problems as a democratic solution.
The "direct action" through demonstrations has become a regular and often effective event.
For less mobile people, this could be replaced by the possibility of expressing their opinion electronically; this ranges from internet chat pages to electronic messages to political leaders.
Then there are non-governmental organizations. They often have undemocratic internal structures, yet they still seem to be more closely connected to citizens.
Furthermore, there is of course the possibility of completely disengaging and leaving politics to experts in order to focus on other aspects of life.
The latter probably poses the greatest risks, because it promotes the creeping authoritarianism that is a sign of our time.
But the other signs of the separation between politics and citizens also create a rather uncertain situation, because no one can anymore say how representative the prevailing views are.
Some want to cut through the knot by increasing direct democracy.
But a lasting connection between leaders and the led cannot be established by reducing public debate to simple voting alternatives.
There would still be much to be said for clinging to the classic institutions of parliamentary democracy and trying to link them more closely with the citizenry again.
After all, unpopular parties and declining voter participation could turn out to be only a temporary phenomenon.
New parties could emerge and inject more life into elections and representative governments.
Yet this is probably not enough to restore the general legitimacy that elected governments have lost.
Therefore, the primary concern of all those who value freedom in the constitution must be to rethink democracy and its institutions.
